<H3>Tuesday, May 13, 2008</H3><A name=3D4912814743730565869></A>
<H2>Spreadsheet file format performance</H2>
<DIV class=3DblogPost>
<DIV style=3D"CLEAR: both"></DIV>I've been doing some performance =
timings of file=20
format support, comparing MS Office and OpenOffice. Most of the results =
are as=20
expected, but some are surprising, and one in particular is quite=20
disappointing.<BR><BR>But first, a little details of my setup. All =
timings, done=20
by stopwatch, were from Office 2003 and OpenOffice 2.4.0 running on =
Windows XP,=20
with all current service packs and patches. The machine is a Lenova =
T60p,=20
dual-core Intel 2.16 Ghz and 2 GB of RAM. I took all the standard =
precautions --=20
disk was defragmented, and test files were confirmed as defragmented =
using <A=20
href=3D"http://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb897428.aspx">co=
ntig</A>.=20
No other applications were running and background tasks were all shut=20
down.<BR><BR>For test files, I went back to an old favorite, George Ou's =
(at the=20
time with ZDNet) monster 50MB XLS file from his <A=20
href=3D"http://blogs.zdnet.com/Ou/?p=3D119">series of tests</A> back in =
2005. This=20
file, although very large, is very simple. There are no formulas, indeed =
no=20
formatting or styles. It is just text and numbers, treating a =
spreadsheet like a=20
giant data table. So tests of this file will emphasize the raw =
throughput of the=20
applications. Real world spreadsheets will typically be worse than this =
due to=20
additional overhead from process styles, formulas, etc.<BR><BR>A test of =
a=20
single file is not really that interesting. We want to see trends, see =
patterns.=20
So I made a set of variations on George's original file, converting it =
into ODF,=20
XLS and OOXML formats, as well as making scaled down versions of it. In =
total I=20
made 12 different sized subsets of the original file, ranging down to a =
437KB=20
version, and created each file in all three formats. I then tested how =
long it=20
took to load each file in each of the applications. In the case of MS =
Office, I=20
installed the current versions of the translators for those formats, the =

Compatibility Pack for OOXML, and the ODF Add-in for the ODF =
support.<BR><BR>I=20
find it convenient to report numbers per 100,000 spreadsheet cells. You =
could=20
equally well use the original XLS spreadsheet size, or the number of =
rows of=20
data, or any other correlated variable as the ordinate, but values per =
100K=20
cells is simple for anyone to understand.<BR><BR>I'll spare you all the =
pretty=20
picture. If you want to make some, here is the <A=20
href=3D"http://www.robweir.com/blog/attachments/FileFormatPerf.csv">raw =
data</A>=20
(CSV format). But I will give some summary observations.<BR><BR><BR>For =
document=20
sizes, the results are as follows:<BR>
<UL>
  <LI>Binary XLS format =3D 1,503 KB per 100K cells
  <LI>OOXML format =3D 491 KB per 100K cells
  <LI>ODF format =3D 117 KB per 100K cells</LI></UL>So the XML formats =
are far=20
smaller than the legacy binary format. This is due to the added Zip =
compression=20
that both XML formats use. Also, note that the ODF files are =
significantly=20
smaller than the OOXML files, less than 1/4 the size on average. Upon =
further=20
examination, the XML document representing the ODF content is larger =
than the=20
corresponding XML in OOXML, as expected, due to its use of longer, more=20
descriptive markup tags. However the ODF XML compresses far better than =
the=20
OOXML version, enough to overcome its greater verbosity and result in =
files=20
smaller than OOXML. The compression ratio (original/zipped) for ODF's=20
content.xml is 87, whereas the compression ratio for OOXML's sheet1.xml =
is only=20
12. We could just mumble something about entropy and walk away, but I =
think this=20
area could bear further investigation.<BR><BR>Any ideas?<BR><BR>For load =
time,=20
the times for processing the binary XLS files were:<BR>
<UL>
  <LI>Microsoft Office 2003 =3D 0.03 seconds per 100K cells
  <LI>OpenOffice 2.4.0 =3D 0.4 seconds per 100K cells</LI></UL>Not too =
surprising.=20
These binary formats are optimized for the guts of MS Office. We would =
expect=20
them to load faster in their native application.<BR><BR>So what about =
the new=20
XML formats? There has been recent talk about the "<A=20
href=3D"http://www.codinghorror.com/blog/archives/001114.html">Angle =
Bracket=20
Tax</A>" for XML formats. How bad is it?<BR>
<UL>
  <LI>Microsoft Office 2003 with OOXML =3D 1.5 seconds per 100K cells
  <LI>OpenOffice 2.4.0 with ODF =3D 2.7 seconds per 100K =
cells</LI></UL>For typical=20
sized documents, you probably will not notice the difference. However =
with the=20
largest documents, like the 16-page, 3-million cells monster sheet, the =
OOXML=20
document took 40 seconds to load in Office, the ODF sheet took 90 =
seconds to=20
load in OpenOffice, whereas the XLS binary took less than 2 seconds to =
load in=20
MS Office.<BR><BR>OK. So what are we missing. Ah, yes, ODF format in MS =
Office,=20
using their ODF Add-in.<BR>
<UL>
  <LI>Microsoft Office 2003 with ODF, using the ODF Add-in =3D 74.6 =
seconds per=20
  100K cells</LI></UL>Yup. You read that right. To put this in =
perspective, let's=20
look at a single test file, a 600K cells file, as we load it in the =
various=20
formats and editors:<BR><BR>
<UL>
  <LI>Microsoft Office 2003 in XLS format =3D 0.75 seconds
  <LI>OpenOffice 2.4.0 in XLS format =3D 3.03 seconds
  <LI>Microsoft Office 2003 in OOXML format =3D 8.28 seconds
  <LI>OpenOffice 2.4.0 in ODF format =3D 14.09 seconds
  <LI>Microsoft Office 2003 in ODF format =3D 515.60 =
seconds</LI></UL>Can someone=20
explain to me why Microsoft Office needs almost 10 minutes to load an =
ODF file=20
that OpenOffice can load in 14 seconds?<BR><BR>(I was not able to test =
files=20
larger than this using the ODF Add-in since they all crashed =
.)<BR><BR>(Update:=20
Since it is the question everyone wants to know, the beta OpenOffice 3.0 =
opens=20
the OOXML version of that file in 49.4 seconds, over 10x faster than MS =
Office=20
loads the ODF document.)<BR><BR>This is one reason why I think file =
format=20
translation is a poor engineering approach to interoperability. When =
OpenOffice=20
wants to read an legacy XLS file, it does not approach the problem by=20
translating the XLS into an ODF document and then loading the ODF file. =
Instead=20
they simply load the XLS file, via a file filter, into the internal =
memory model=20
of OpenOffice.<BR><BR>What is a file filter? It is like 1/2 of a =
translator.=20
Instead of translating from one disk format to another disk format, it =
simply=20
loads the disk format and maps it into an application-specific memory =
model that=20
the application logic can operate directly on. This is far more =
efficient than=20
translation. This is the untold truth that the layperson does not know. =
But this=20
is how everyone does it. That is how we support formats in SmartSuite. =
That is=20
how OpenOffice does it. And that is how MS Office does it for the file =
formats=20
they care about. In fact, that is the way that Novell is now doing it =
now, since=20
they discovered that the Microsoft approach is doomed to performance=20
hell.<BR><BR>So it is with some amusement that I watch Microsoft and =
others=20
propose translation as a solution to interoperability, creating reports =
about=20
translation, even a proposal for a new work item in JTC1/SC34 concerning =
file=20
format translation, when the single concrete attempt at translation is =
such an=20
abysmal failure. It may look great on paper, but it is an engineering =
disaster.=20
What customers need is direct, internal support for ODF in MS Office, =
via native=20
code, in a file filter, not a translator that takes 10 minutes to load a =

file.<BR><BR>The astute engineer will agree with the above, but will =
also feel=20
some discomfort at the numbers. There is more here than can be explained =
simply=20
by the use of translators versus import filters. That choice might =
explain a 2x=20
difference in performance. A particularly poor implementation might =
explain a 5x=20
difference. But none of this explains why MS Office is almost 40x slower =
in=20
processing ODF files. Being that much slower is hard to do accidentally. =
Other=20
forces must be at play.<BR><BR>Any ideas?
